:''Not to be confused with [[financial repression]], a method of liquidating government debt.'' '''Economic repression''' comprises various actions to restrain certain [[economy|economical]] activities or [[social group]]s involved in economic activities. It contrasts with [[economic liberalization]]. Economists note widespread economic repression in [[developing countries]].<ref name=jha/><ref name=bhag/><ref>[[Anne Krueger]] (1978) "Foreign Trade Attempts & Economic Development: Liberalization Attempts and Consequences" {{ISBN|0-88410-483-4}}</ref>
The main goal of economic repression is [[protectionism]], the instruments for which include [[Fine (penalty)|fines]] and ceilings on [[interest rate]]s or [[exchange rate]]s.<ref name=jha>Raghbendra Jha, "Macroeconomics for Developing Countries", [https://books.google.com/books?id=BeqFbtRH9YEC&pg=PA393&lpg=PA393&dq=%22economic+repression+is%22&source=web&ots=0BRPW05Bqj&sig=RiSSKcqSdQxP5uQi_qstF_0gToU&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result p. 393]</ref><ref name=bhag> [[Jagdish Bhagwati]] (1989) "Protectionism", {{ISBN|0-262-52150-4}}</ref>
A common type of economic repression against individuals is [[blacklisting]].<ref>"Encyclopedia of American Civil Liberties", ed. [[Paul Finkelman]], vol. 1: A-F (2006) {{ISBN|0-415-94342-6}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=YoI14vYA8r0C&pg=PA150&dq=%22economic+repression%22+soviet&lr= p. 150, article "Blacklisting" by Anthony Chase ]</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Imperfect competition| ]]
{{econ-stub}}

'''Gas immersion laser doping''' ('''GILD''') is a method of [[Doping (semiconductor)|doping]] a [[semiconductor]] material such as [[silicon]].

In the case of doping silicon with boron to create a [[P-type semiconductor]] material, a thin [[Wafer (electronics)|wafer]] of silicon is placed in a containment chamber and is immersed in boron gas. A pulsed laser is directed at the silicon wafer and this results in localised melting and subsequent recrystalisation of the silicon wafer material, allowing boron atoms in the gas to diffuse into the molten sections of the silicon wafer.<ref name="Gas immersion laser doping (GILD) for ultra-shallow junction formation">{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title= Gas immersion laser doping (GILD) for ultra-shallow junction formation |url= http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0040609003016687 |website=Elsevier ScienceDirect |location= |publisher= |date= |language=English |accessdate=2017-10-03}}</ref> The end result of this process is a silicon wafer with boron impurities, creating a P-type semiconductor.

